The standard .NET approach is to use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package. It wraps the static `System.IO` calls behind injectable interfaces.

**Steps:**

1. `dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions`
2. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes instead of calling `File.*` / `Directory.*` directly:

```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path) => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);
    public void Save(string path, string content) => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);
    public bool CheckDir(string path) => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

3. In production, register the real implementation:
```csharp
services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem>(new FileSystem());
```

4. In tests, use the companion package `System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers`:
```csharp
var fs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{ }") }
});
var svc = new MyService(fs);
Assert.True(svc.CheckDir("/data"));
```

This avoids touching the real disk in tests, keeps your code easy to reason about, and is the most widely adopted pattern in the .NET ecosystem.
